  "prompt": "Why does pubic and body hair stop growing after it reaches a certain length?",
  "response": "Body hair, including pubic hair, has a growth cycle that consists of three main phases: anagen (growth phase), catagen (transition phase), and telogen (resting phase). The length that body hair reaches before it stops growing is determined by the duration of the anagen phase.\n\n1. **Anagen Phase**: In this phase, hair actively grows. The length of the anagen phase varies by body location. For example, the anagen phase for scalp hair can last several years, allowing it to grow much longer, while the anagen phase for body and pubic hair is typically much shorter\u2014weeks to a couple of years. Once the hair reaches the end of its anagen phase, it stops growing.\n\n2. **Catagen Phase**: After the anagen phase, hair enters the catagen phase, which lasts a few weeks. During this phase, hair growth stops, and the hair follicle shrinks, preparing for the next stage.\n\n3. **Telogen Phase**: Finally, during the telogen phase, which can last several months, the hair is dormant and may eventually shed. This phase leads to the initiation of a new hair growth cycle.\n\nThe genetic and hormonal factors influence how long the anagen phase lasts for different types of hair. This is why body and pubic hair have a characteristic length\u2014they simply do not grow as long as scalp hair because their growth phases are shorter.",
